content.description: Start on the arete and go up to a big jug on the arete.
content.location: The right side of the boulder.

content.description: Trolley Dyno is a fun and easy, one move wonder, dyno problem.
content.location: Start on an edge a few feet to the right of the left arete (Kids Can't Climb), dyno straight up and a little to the right to a jug, and finish on jugs.

content.description: This is a low traverse that starts on the left arete and goes to the right arete. From the right arete, you go to the top.
content.location: The start is the same as for Nick Came Back With a Whole Catastrophe .

content.description: Start as for Up And Up Again, traverse left, and go up Kids Can't Climb. Basically this is a reverse of Tram and the Trolley but is slightly easier. Big ledges below climb are obviously off for your feet.
content.protection: A couple pads and someone to move the pads.
content.location: It is on the right side of the boulder.

content.description: This is on the face on the right side of the boulder, and you canâ€™t use any holds on the other side of the arete.
content.location: Start with your left hand on a sidepull thing, and with your right, try to squeeze a few fingers into a small pocket next to the tree (this may be harder for people with thicker fingers). Then, go straight up, using edges, slopers and jugs to the top.

content.description:
Start with your left hand in a good, V-shaped groove on the left face and your right hand on an undercling/sidepull on the right face. Climb straight up the arete using holds on both faces.

 This could be harder if you're tall, since the start is pretty scrunchy.

Dyno off an awkward start to a good ledge. Start on the edge rail slightly to the left of Trolley Dyno, and plant some good feet. Dyno straight up to the large jug avoiding any other holds around it. Then top out. It is a little bit of an eliminate and is very contrived.Tip: the jug is really sharp, and it is less sharp around the left side of it.
content.location: A foot to the left of Trolley Dyno, it is contrived.

climbs.name: Nick Came Back With a Whole Catastrophe

content.description: This starts on the left arete with two hand holds. It continues right until you get to the flat face, then go up. This route is more fun if you only use the crimps on the flat face and not the jugs on the left and right. Most of the holds to get the crimp section are jugs too.
content.location: Start at the far left, and go to the middle.

content.description: Nailed It is a short, powerful problem that uses a cool gaston jug.
content.location: Sit start 10 feet to the left of Goosebumps with your left hand on the arete and your right hand on a slopey crimp in the middle of the face. Do a move up to a good left hand gaston, then slap your left hand up the arete, and finish on jugs. Run up the ridge, and top out.

content.description: This starts on the left arete and just goes up it. Really use whatever you want.
content.location: It is on the left side of the boulder.

content.description: Start anywhere, and climb the slab using small crimps and good knobs for your feet.
content.location: This climbs the steepest part of the slab on the left side of the boulder.

content.description: Sit start on jugs under Up and Up Again on the right side of the face. Move out left on juggy sidepulls, move to the big ledge, and top out left of the arete. This is a fun one.
content.location: It is on the right side of the main face.

content.description:
There is a lot of easy stuff on this boulder. It is very good for warming up on. There is a slab on this boulder too if anyone would want to take the time to clean it. It also looks very easy. 

  The GPS location is incorrect, I don't know how to fix it.
